You are developing an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

To avoid duplicate code and stay consistent as the project grows, you MUST follow these context and reuse rules.
When in doubt, search first and reuse — never write new code without checking for existing equivalents.

==============================
SEARCH BEFORE WRITING
==============================

Before adding ANY of the following, search the codebase first:

- A new function or utility
  → Search in packages/shared/src/utils/, apps/api/src/common/, apps/web/src/lib/
- A new type or interface
  → Search in packages/shared/src/types/, and in the same module's dto/ or types/
- A new validation schema
  → Search in packages/shared/src/schemas/
- A new constant, enum, or config value
  → Search in packages/shared/src/constants/, and in module-level constants
- A new React component (e.g. modal, button variant, form field)
  → Search in apps/web/src/components/ui/ and in the relevant feature folder (fair/, customer/)
- A new hook (e.g. useDebounce, useLocalStorage)
  → Search in apps/web/src/hooks/
- A new NestJS guard, pipe, or interceptor
  → Search in apps/api/src/common/

If you find something that does the same or similar:
- Reuse it (import and use), or
- Extend it (add a parameter or option), or
- Refactor once to make it generic and use in both places.

Do NOT add a second copy. Do NOT write a new implementation without referencing the existing one.

==============================
USE EXISTING MODULES AS TEMPLATES
==============================

When adding a new domain module (e.g. customer, user, upload):

- Consult .cursor/rules/reference-modules.mdc for the REFERENCE MODULE REGISTRY.
- Identify the correct template module and verify it is available (feature completed).
- If template is available: read that module's files before writing:
  - Same folder layout (module, controller, service, dto/, etc.)
  - Same naming (e.g. fair.service.ts → customer.service.ts)
  - Same patterns (how DTOs are used, how Prisma is called, how responses are shaped)
- If template is NOT yet available: follow Pre-Reference Phase rules in reference-modules.mdc.
- Mirror the structure and patterns. Only the domain logic should differ.

The reference-modules.mdc registry tracks all template modules with their availability status.
Always check that registry instead of guessing which module to reference.

When implementing a new module, list the template files you are following at the start of your implementation.

==============================
SHARED AND COMMON FIRST
==============================

- Error messages, success messages, and user-facing strings that may be reused
  → Prefer constants in packages/shared/src/constants/ or a messages/ file; do not scatter identical strings.
- Validation logic used in more than one place
  → Must live in packages/shared (Zod schemas) or in a shared pipe/helper; do not duplicate in each module.
- Formatting (dates, numbers, currency)
  → Must use packages/shared/src/utils/ (e.g. formatDate, formatBudget); do not redefine in api or web.
- API response shape
  → Use types from @crm/shared; do not redefine equivalent interfaces in api or web.

If you are about to copy-paste a block of code to a second place, stop and move that logic to a shared location instead.

==============================
SCOPE AND CONTEXT
==============================

When working on a feature:

- At the start, list the existing files that are relevant (e.g. fair.service.ts, fair.controller.ts, create-fair.schema.ts).
- For each new file you add, name the existing file(s) it should align with (e.g. "customer.service.ts follows the pattern of fair.service.ts").
- If the codebase is large and you are unsure whether something already exists, say so and suggest a quick search (e.g. by function name or string) before writing.

This reduces mistakes when the project grows and not all files fit in context.

==============================
SMALL ADDITIONS
==============================

Even for small changes (a new helper, a new component, a new constant):

- Run a quick mental/search check: "Is there already something like this?"
- If yes, reuse or extend. If no, add it in the correct place (shared vs app-specific) and follow existing naming and structure.

Do not add one-off helpers or duplicate strings "just for this file" if they could be shared.

==============================
IMPORTANT
==============================

- These rules apply in every conversation, regardless of feature number.
- Violating these rules (e.g. adding duplicate logic or ignoring an existing util) is not acceptable even if the code "works".
- When the user asks you to implement something, assume you must search and reuse first unless the user explicitly asks for a new standalone implementation.
